# Git & PR Workflow

## Branches

- `main` is deployable at all times.
- Pre-v1, branch all feature/fix/chore/prompt work from `main`.
- Do not push directly to `main`; use pull requests for all normal changes.
- Feature branches: `feat/<short-description>` (e.g., `feat/opus-model-support`).
- Fixes: `fix/<short-description>`.
- Prompt changes: `prompt/<description>` — these trigger evals in CI.

## Commits

- Conventional Commits: `feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`, `docs:`, `test:`, `refactor:`.
- Subject line under 72 characters.
- Body explains WHY, not WHAT (the diff shows what).
- Reference issues: `Closes #123` in the body.
- Don't commit commented-out code. Delete it; Git remembers.

## Pull requests

- One logical change per PR. If you're adding a feature and refactoring, those are two PRs.
- Pre-v1 default PR base is `main` unless the user/maintainer specifies another base.
- PR title mirrors the commit message (squash merge produces one commit).
- Description template:
  ```
  ## What
  <1–2 sentences>

  ## Why
  <context/motivation>

  ## How
  <key design decisions>

  ## Testing
  <how you verified, screenshots if UI>

  ## Risk
  <what could break, rollback plan>
  ```
- Mark as draft until you're confident it's reviewable.

## Review expectations

- Reviewer SLA: same day for small PRs, 48h for large PRs.
- At least one approval required for merge.
- CI must be green. No force-merges.
- If you push changes after review, re-request review explicitly.

## Merging

- Squash merge into `main`. Preserves clean history.
- Delete the branch after merging.
- If the PR introduces a schema or API breaking change, the PR title must start with `!` (e.g., `feat!: rename reviews to pr_reviews`).

## Hotfixes

- Create `hotfix/<description>` from `main`.
- Fix, test, open PR, get one approval, merge, deploy.
- Post-mortem within 48h.
